conceptCard.title: AI for Personalized Learning: AI-powered personalized learning, adaptive content delivery, or intelligent tutoring systems to support student learning.
conceptCard.description: This case explores AI systems that adapt educational content and pacing to individual student needs, providing personalized learning pathways and intelligent tutoring support. The goal is to optimize learning outcomes while ensuring equitable access and preventing algorithmic bias.
conceptCard.payer: Educational institutions, school districts, and online learning platforms investing in personalized education technology.
conceptCard.endUser: Students who interact with the AI system for learning, and teachers who monitor and guide the personalized learning process.
conceptCard.servicingParty: Educational technology company or AI learning platform provider responsible for content creation, algorithm development, and system optimization.
conceptCard.impactedIndividuals: Students from diverse backgrounds whose learning paths are determined by AI algorithms, including those with learning disabilities or different learning styles.
conceptCard.doAct: Dynamically adjust content difficulty, provide real-time feedback, and recommend personalized learning activities based on individual progress.
conceptCard.inferReason: Analyze learning patterns, knowledge gaps, and engagement levels to infer optimal content sequencing and intervention strategies.
conceptCard.data1: Student interaction data including time spent on topics, correct/incorrect responses, and learning pathway choices.
conceptCard.data2: Educational content metadata, difficulty ratings, and prerequisite relationships between concepts.
conceptCard.data3: Student learning profiles, cognitive assessments, and historical performance across different subjects.
conceptCard.data4: Demographic information, learning preferences, and accessibility requirements for equitable algorithm design.

values.definition: A fair AI system supports all learners equally. It avoids reinforcing bias and works well regardless of students' race, gender, ability, or background.

tensions.definition: Making the AI system fairer may require collecting more detailed information about students to detect and reduce bias. But collecting that kind of data can raise privacy concerns.

conceptCard.title: AI for Classroom Management: Using AI to assist with classroom management, such as monitoring student engagement, automating attendance, or flagging disruptions.
conceptCard.description: This case explores the use of AI-powered tools to help teachers manage classrooms more efficiently, including real-time engagement tracking, automated attendance, and early warning for disruptions. The goal is to support teachers while ensuring student privacy and fairness.
conceptCard.payer: School District or Educational Institution funding the AI system for classroom management and teacher support.
conceptCard.endUser: Teachers and classroom staff who interact with the AI system daily to monitor and manage students.
conceptCard.servicingParty: EdTech company or IT department responsible for deploying, maintaining, and updating the AI system.
conceptCard.impactedIndividuals: Students whose engagement, attendance, and behavior are monitored by the AI system, and their parents/guardians.
conceptCard.doAct: Automatically record attendance, flag disengaged students, and alert teachers to possible disruptions in real time.
conceptCard.inferReason: Analyze engagement data to infer which students may need additional support or intervention.
conceptCard.data1: Student engagement metrics (e.g., eye contact, participation, device usage).
conceptCard.data2: Attendance records and historical classroom behavior data.
conceptCard.data3: Teacher notes and feedback on student participation and classroom climate.
conceptCard.data4: Demographic information and learning profiles for each student.

values.definition: An autonomy-supporting AI system gives students and teachers control. It avoids making decisions for them and offers meaningful choices.
